<div id="review_882601205" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/882601205" />
    <a title="Sherry Elmer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20805054-sherry-elmer"><img alt="Sherry Elmer" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1369803487p2/20805054.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/882601205?book_show_action=true">Mar 15, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sherry Elmer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sherry Elmer" href="/user/show/20805054-sherry-elmer">Sherry Elmer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">fans of mythology; fans of C.S. Lewis</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20805054-sherry-elmer?shelf=2017">2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20805054-sherry-elmer?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20805054-sherry-elmer?shelf=thinking-authors">thinking-authors</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20805054-sherry-elmer?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20805054-sherry-elmer?shelf=c-s-lewis">c-s-lewis</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20805054-sherry-elmer?shelf=worth-reading-again">worth-reading-again</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20805054-sherry-elmer?shelf=2020">2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer882601205" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15917122817145119464">This is the third time for me to read this book, and I only started it again because the Ambleside online moms were reading it. Although I loved the book, I did not feel a reread was important at this time. But, since my lovely friends were reading, why not?<br/>On this third reading I was stopped after just the first paragraph: “I am old now and have not much to fear from the gods. I have no husband nor child, nor hardly a friend, through whom they can hurt me.”<br/>This hurt to read. It was only the day</span>
  <span id="freeText15917122817145119464" style="display:none">This is the third time for me to read this book, and I only started it again because the Ambleside online moms were reading it. Although I loved the book, I did not feel a reread was important at this time. But, since my lovely friends were reading, why not?<br />On this third reading I was stopped after just the first paragraph: “I am old now and have not much to fear from the gods. I have no husband nor child, nor hardly a friend, through whom they can hurt me.”<br />This hurt to read. It was only the day before that I had thought almost the same thing, although not so eloquently. I had the thought that it is time for a new dream, and immediately I had the follow-up thought, “Having a dream is a fast way to be sure it won’t come true.” The thought shamed me, because the thought was a (wrong) judgement of God. He has proved Himself so many times, and yet… Do I still sometimes find myself thinking, as Lewis said in another book, “We are not necessarily doubting that God will do the best for us; we are wondering how painful the best will turn out to be.” I could see that I was. <br />And that is what I find this book excelling at—inciting me to examine myself, to check my motives, to probe the inner recesses of my heart. I can think of no other novel that affects me more powerfully in this way. <br />Which means that although I love this book, reading it isn’t necessarily a pleasant experience. But it is a good and needful one, and for that I am thankful. I am thankful, too, for the readers at Ambleside online for inspiring me to read this again at such a time as this. <br /><br />February 21, 2020<br /><br /><br /><br /><br />I once heard someone ask, What if you spent your whole life climbing to the top of the proverbial ladder only to discover that the ladder had been leaning against the wrong building all along. I can imagine how devastating this would be. Buy how much worse to discover at the end of your life that the person you thought you were was an illusion, and you are actually the last thing you ever wanted to be. <br /><br />This is one of the questions C.S. Lewis raises in this profound book. Till We Have Faces begins as a retelling of the ancient Cupid and Psyche story, but by the end, it grabs you by the throat and forces you to look into the mirror, much the way Orual's father once did to her. Maybe that look will not be too painful. Or, maybe, like Orual, you will say, “'I am Ungit.' Without question it was true. It was I who was Ungit. That ruinous face was mine. I was that Batta-thing, that all-devouring womblike, yet barren, thing. Glome was a web—I was the swollen spider, squat at its center, gorged with men's stolen lives.”</span>
  <a data-text-id="15917122817145119464" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


