    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1686996610" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1686996610" />
    <a title="Hana" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10571559-hana"><img alt="Hana" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1458172215p2/10571559.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1686996610?book_show_action=true">Jul 03, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hana" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hana" href="/user/show/10571559-hana">Hana</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10571559-hana?shelf=2016-reads">2016-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10571559-hana?shelf=fantasy-sci-fi">fantasy-sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1686996610" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12835520500351667901">Jealousy, insecurity and abuse are the toxic and combustible fuels that fire this story of a tribal royal family. Great storytelling with memorable characters who even in their failures engage the reader. I kept turning the pages compulsively until the final fifty pages [more later].<br/><br/><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17343.Till_We_Have_Faces' title='Till We Have Faces by C.S. Lewis' rel='nofollow noopener'>Till We Have Faces</a> also intersected rather neatly and serendipitously with my current non-fiction read <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1831667.The_Horse__the_Wheel_and_Language_How_Bronze_Age_Riders_from_the_Eurasian_Steppes_Shaped_the_Modern_World' title='The Horse, the Wheel and Language How Bronze-Age Riders from the Eurasian Steppes Shaped the Modern World by David W. Anthony' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Horse, the Wheel and Language: How Bronze-Age Riders from the Eurasian Steppes Shaped the Modern World</a>. My 19</span>
  <span id="freeText12835520500351667901" style="display:none">Jealousy, insecurity and abuse are the toxic and combustible fuels that fire this story of a tribal royal family. Great storytelling with memorable characters who even in their failures engage the reader. I kept turning the pages compulsively until the final fifty pages [more later].<br /><br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17343.Till_We_Have_Faces" title="Till We Have Faces by C.S. Lewis" rel="nofollow noopener">Till We Have Faces</a> also intersected rather neatly and serendipitously with my current non-fiction read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1831667.The_Horse__the_Wheel_and_Language_How_Bronze_Age_Riders_from_the_Eurasian_Steppes_Shaped_the_Modern_World" title="The Horse, the Wheel and Language How Bronze-Age Riders from the Eurasian Steppes Shaped the Modern World by David W. Anthony" rel="nofollow noopener">The Horse, the Wheel and Language: How Bronze-Age Riders from the Eurasian Steppes Shaped the Modern World</a>. My 1956 edition of Lewis' novel has vaguely Egyptian and Mesopotamian illustrations but Lewis' fantasy kingdom of Glome has more in common with the Bronze Age cultures around the Black Sea that <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/836966.David_W__Anthony" title="David W. Anthony" rel="nofollow noopener">David W. Anthony</a> studies. <br /><br />Glome is a world under constant threat and now facing the inexorable reality of change. Marginal farm-based economies; constantly shifting tribal rivalries; threats from other cultures (mostly the Greeks as embodied by a marvelous character, The Fox, tutor and counselor extraordinaire); an old female-centered religion decaying at the head but still moving the populace; an equally old male-centered military culture looking towards blood-letting as the route to wealth and domination. Glome is also a land in which human sacrifice, the sacrifice not of willing warriors but of the innocent, is ennobled. Onto this scene come three royal sisters of Glome: one so ugly that her only hope seems to be to veil herself, one born so beautiful that those who see her declare her a goddess, and one whose desires and devices might bring her sisters and the kingdom to an end.<br /><br />Alas, the last fifty pages....<br /><br />You know how it is when you are almost on the edge of waking up? And you are in the middle of dream that's mostly boring and doesn't make much sense? And part of your brain is saying this is a dumb dream! Yup! Part II is just like that. <br /><br />Part II is the sort of thing PC editors of the author's time insisted that the writer add. It's the sort of thing writer feel they have to add because...they want to prove they are smart, with it, whatever. My recommendation wake yourself up before Part II, forget all the commentary about Psyche and Cupid, etc., and just enjoy the book as pure fantasy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12835520500351667901" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


